<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="101" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="101">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="101">
Kozlov described 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Platygastridae" genus="Anirama" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anirama" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anirama</taxonomicName>
as a genus separate from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Platygaster" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platygaster" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Platygaster</taxonomicName>
because the apical antennomere of the male is elongate. There are otherwise no characters to indicate that this lineage is distinct from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Platygaster" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platygaster" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Platygaster</taxonomicName>
and we consider this antennal morphology to be apomorphic within 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Platygaster" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platygaster" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Platygaster</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
